Chiyonoyama Masanobu.label: Chiyonoyama Masanobu
Chiyonoyama Masanobu.description: Chiyonoyama Masanobu was a sumo wrestler from Fukushima, Hokkaidō, Japan. He was the sport's 41st Yokozuna. He was also the founder of Kokonoe stable. Wikipedia

Kotofuji Takaya.label: Kotofuji Takaya
Kotofuji Takaya.description: Kotofuji Takaya is a former sumo wrestler from Chiba City, Japan. His highest rank was sekiwake. In 1991 he won a top division yūshō or tournament championship from the maegashira ranks. Wikipedia
Kotofuji Takaya.Born: October 28, 1964 (age 49), Hanamigawa-ku, Chiba, Chiba Prefecture, Japan

Shōhōzan Yūya.label: Shōhōzan Yūya
Shōhōzan Yūya.description: Shōhōzan Yūya is a sumo wrestler from Chikujō, Fukuoka, Japan. The highest rank he has reached is komusubi. Wikipedia
Shōhōzan Yūya.Born: February 9, 1984 (age 30), Chikujō, Fukuoka, Fukuoka Prefecture, Japan

Takanonami Sadahiro.label: Takanonami Sadahiro
Takanonami Sadahiro.description: Takanonami Sadahiro is a former sumo wrestler from Aomori, Japan. He held sumo's second highest rank of ōzeki from 1994 until 2000 and won two tournament titles. He is now a sumo coach. Wikipedia

Takashi Ishikawa.label: Takashi Ishikawa
Takashi Ishikawa.description: Takashi Ishikawa is a former professional wrestler and sumo wrestler from Fujishima, Higashitagawa District, Yamagata Prefecture, Japan. Wikipedia

Asahikuni Masuo.label: Asahikuni Masuo
Asahikuni Masuo.description: Asahikuni Masuo is a former sumo wrestler from Hokkaidō, Japan. His highest rank was ōzeki. After his retirement he set up Ōshima stable which he ran from 1980 until he left the Japan Sumo Association in 2012 upon reaching the age of 65. Wikipedia

Akinoumi Setsuo.label: Akinoumi Setsuo
Akinoumi Setsuo.description: Akinoumi Setsuo was a sumo wrestler from Hiroshima, Japan. He was the sport's 37th Yokozuna. Wikipedia

Hamanishiki Tatsurō.label: Hamanishiki Tatsurō
Hamanishiki Tatsurō.description: Hamanishiki Tatsurō is a former sumo wrestler from Kumamoto, Japan. A former amateur champion, he made his professional debut in 1999. His highest rank was maegashira 11, which he reached in 2002. Wikipedia

Katayama Shinji.label: Katayama Shinji
Katayama Shinji.description: Katayama Shinji is a former sumo wrestler from Yaizu, Shizuoka, Japan. His highest rank was maegashira 13. Wikipedia

Kitazakura Hidetoshi.label: Kitazakura Hidetoshi
Kitazakura Hidetoshi.description: Kitazakura Hidetoshi, born December 15, 1971 as Hidetoshi Mukō is a former sumo wrestler from Asakita ward, Hiroshima City, Japan. His highest rank was maegashira 9. He is the elder brother of Toyozakura, also a top division wrestler. Wikipedia
Kitazakura Hidetoshi.Born: December 15, 1971 (age 42), Asakita-ku, Hiroshima, Hiroshima Prefecture, Japan

Kotogahama Sadao.label: Kotogahama Sadao
Kotogahama Sadao.description:
Kotogahama Sadao was a sumo wrestler from Kanonji, Kagawa, Japan.
He reached the second highest rank of ōzeki in 1958. Wikipedia

Kotonishiki Katsuhiro.label: Kotonishiki Katsuhiro
Kotonishiki Katsuhiro.description: Kotonishiki Katsuhiro is a former sumo wrestler from Takasaki, Gunma Prefecture, Japan. He began his career in 1984, reaching the top makuuchi division in 1989. Wikipedia

Musashiyama Takeshi.label: Musashiyama Takeshi
Musashiyama Takeshi.description: Musashiyama Takeshi was a sumo wrestler from Yokohama, Kanagawa Prefecture, Japan. He was the sport's 33rd Yokozuna. He had a rapid rise through the ranks, setting several youth records, and was very popular with the public. Wikipedia
Musashiyama Takeshi.Born: December 5, 1909, Kōhoku-ku, Yokohama, Kanagawa Prefecture, Japan

Toyozakura Toshiaki.label: Toyozakura Toshiaki
Toyozakura Toshiaki.description: Toyozakura Toshiaki is a former sumo wrestler from Hiroshima, Japan. He made his debut in 1989, and after many years in the lower ranks he reached the top division for the first time in 2003. His highest rank was maegashira 5. Wikipedia
Toyozakura Toshiaki.Born: March 12, 1974 (age 40), Asakita-ku, Hiroshima, Hiroshima Prefecture, Japan

Tsunenohana Kan'ichi.label: Tsunenohana Kan'ichi
Tsunenohana Kan'ichi.description: Tsunenohana Kan'ichi was a sumo wrestler from Okayama, Japan. He was the sport's 31st Yokozuna. Wikipedia

Wakamisugi Akiteru.label: Wakamisugi Akiteru
Wakamisugi Akiteru.description: Wakamisugi Akiteru was a sumo wrestler from Kagawa, Japan. The highest rank he achieved was sekiwake. He was the brother in law of yokozuna Wakanohana Kanji I. Wikipedia

Washūyama Yoshikazu.label: Washūyama Yoshikazu
Washūyama Yoshikazu.description: Washūyama Yoshikazu is a former sumo wrestler from Kurashiki, Okayama, Japan. His highest rank was sekiwake. He is now the head coach of Dewanoumi stable. Wikipedia

Kiyokuni Katsuo.label: Kiyokuni Katsuo
Kiyokuni Katsuo.description: Kiyokuni Katsuo is a former sumo wrestler from Ogachi, Akita, Japan. His highest rank was ōzeki, which he held from 1969 to 1974. He won one top division yūshō or tournament championship and was a runner-up in five other tournaments. Wikipedia

Kokkai Futoshi.label: Kokkai Futoshi
Kokkai Futoshi.description: Kokkai Futoshi is a former professional sumo wrestler from Georgia. He began his career in May 2001. He is the first European rikishi to reach sumo's highest division, makuuchi, which he achieved in 2004. Wikipedia

Sadanoyama Shinmatsu.label: Sadanoyama Shinmatsu
Sadanoyama Shinmatsu.description: Sadanoyama Shinmatsu is a former sumo wrestler from Nagasaki Prefecture, Japan. He was the sport's 50th Yokozuna. After his retirement he was the head coach of Dewanoumi stable and served as head of the Japan Sumo Association. Wikipedia

Takamiyama Daigorō.label: Takamiyama Daigorō
Takamiyama Daigorō.description: Takamiyama Daigorō 高見山大五郎 is a former sumo wrestler, the first foreign born rikishi to win the top division championship. His highest rank was sekiwake. Wikipedia

Terao Tsunefumi.label: Terao Tsunefumi
Terao Tsunefumi.description: Terao Tsunefumi is a former sumo wrestler. He was born in Tokyo, but brought up in Kajiki, Aira District, Kagoshima, Japan. He fought out of Izutsu stable. The highest rank he reached was sekiwake. Wikipedia

Sentoryū Henri.label: Sentoryū Henri
Sentoryū Henri.description: Henry Armstrong Miller is a former sumo wrestler, raised in St. Louis, Missouri, United States, who competed under the shikona Sentoryū Henri. Wikipedia

Chiyotenzan Daihachirō.label: Chiyotenzan Daihachirō
Chiyotenzan Daihachirō.description: Chiyotenzan Daihachirō is a former sumo wrestler from Osaka, Japan. His highest rank was komusubi. Wikipedia

Tokitsuumi Masahiro.label: Tokitsuumi Masahiro
Tokitsuumi Masahiro.description: Tokitsuumi Masahiro is a former professional sumo wrestler from Fukue, Nagasaki, Japan. A former amateur sumo champion, he turned professional in 1996. His highest rank was maegashira 3. Wikipedia

Yoshibayama Junnosuke.label: Yoshibayama Junnosuke
Yoshibayama Junnosuke.description: Yoshibayama Junnosuke, real name Junnosuke Ikeda, was a sumo wrestler from Atsuta, Hokkaidō, Japan. He was the sport's 43rd Yokozuna. He suffered a number of injuries and only won one tournament championship, but he was a popular wrestler. Wikipedia

Ōtsukasa Nobuhide.label: Ōtsukasa Nobuhide
Ōtsukasa Nobuhide.description: Ōtsukasa Nobuhide is a former sumo wrestler from Miki, Hyōgo, Japan. A former amateur champion, he made his professional debut in 1993. The highest rank he reached was maegashira 4. He retired in March 2009 and is now a sumo coach. Wikipedia

Kaiketsu Masateru.label: Kaiketsu Masateru
Kaiketsu Masateru.description: Kaiketsu Masateru is a former sumo wrestler, who reached the second highest rank of ōzeki on two separate occasions. He also won two top division tournament championships. Wikipedia

Ouchiyama Heikichi.label: Ōuchiyama Heikichi
Ouchiyama Heikichi.description:
Ōuchiyama Heikichi was a sumo wrestler from Hitachinaka, Ibaraki, Japan.
He joined Tokitsukaze stable in 1944 and reached the top makuuchi division in 1949. Wikipedia

Ōnishiki Uichirō.label: Ōnishiki Uichirō
Ōnishiki Uichirō.description: Ōnishiki Uichirō was a sumo wrestler. He was the sport's 26th Yokozuna. On November 2, 1922, he became the first yokozuna to perform the yokozuna dohyō-iri at the Meiji Shrine. Wikipedia
Ōnishiki Uichirō.Born: November 25, 1891, Chūō-ku, Osaka, Osaka Prefecture, Japan

Daishōyama Naoki.label: Daishōyama Naoki
Daishōyama Naoki.description: Daishōyama Naoki is a former sumo wrestler from Anamizu, Ishikawa, Japan. A former amateur champion, he made his professional debut in January 1989 and reached a highest rank of maegashira 2 before retiring in 1995. Wikipedia

Gojōrō Katsuhiro.label: Gojōrō Katsuhiro
Gojōrō Katsuhiro.description: Gojōrō Katsuhiro is a former sumo wrestler from Aoba-ku, Sendai, Japan. Making his professional debut in 1989, he spent a total of 53 tournaments as an elite sekitori ranked wrestler, reaching a highest rank of maegashira 3 in 1998. Wikipedia
Gojōrō Katsuhiro.Born: August 18, 1973 (age 40), Aoba-ku, Sendai, Miyagi Prefecture, Japan

Hakuba Takeshi.label: Hakuba Takeshi
Hakuba Takeshi.description: Hakuba Takeshi is a former sumo wrestler from Ulan Bator, Mongolia. Joining the professional sport in 2000, he entered the top division for the first time in 2008, returning in 2010. His highest rank was komusubi. Wikipedia

Kitataiki Akeyoshi.label: Kitataiki Akeyoshi
Kitataiki Akeyoshi.description: Kitataiki Akeyoshi is a professional sumo wrestler from Machida City, Tokyo, Japan. Making his debut in March 1998, he reached the top division for the first time in September 2008, returning in January 2010. Wikipedia

Mōkonami Sakae.label: Mōkonami Sakae
Mōkonami Sakae.description: Mōkonami Sakae is a former sumo wrestler from Mongolia. After making his professional sumo debut in March 2001, he had his top makuuchi division debut 8 years later in July 2009. His highest rank was maegashira 6. Wikipedia

Ōzutsu Man'emon.label: Ōzutsu Man'emon
Ōzutsu Man'emon.description: Ōzutsu Man'emon was a sumo wrestler from Shiroishi, Miyagi Prefecture, Japan. He was the sport's 18th Yokozuna. Wikipedia

Hidenoyama Raigorō.label: Hidenoyama Raigorō
Hidenoyama Raigorō.description: Hidenoyama Raigorō was a sumo wrestler from Kesennuma, Miyagi Prefecture, Japan. He was the sport's 9th Yokozuna. He was also known as Amatsukaze Kumoemon, Tatsugami Kumoemon and Iwamigata Jōemon. Wikipedia

Maruyama Gondazaemon.label: Maruyama Gondazaemon
Maruyama Gondazaemon.description: Maruyama Gondazaemon was a sumo wrestler. He is officially recognised as the third yokozuna. His real name was Haga Gindayu. He came from a village in the Sendai Domain. Wikipedia

Bushūyama Takashi.label: Bushūyama Takashi
Bushūyama Takashi.description: Bushūyama Takashi is a Japanese former sumo wrestler from Aomori, Aomori Prefecture. He made his professional debut in January 1999. At the age of 32, he was promoted to the top makuuchi division in the November 2008 tournament. Wikipedia

Tamanofuji Shigeru.label: Tamanofuji Shigeru
Tamanofuji Shigeru.description: Tamanofuji Shigeru is a former sumo wrestler from Ogawa, Nasu District, Tochigi Prefecture, Japan. Wikipedia
Tamanofuji Shigeru.Born: November 24, 1949 (age 64), Nakagawa, Tochigi, Tochigi Prefecture, Japan

Ōzutsu Takeshi.label: Ōzutsu Takeshi
Ōzutsu Takeshi.description: Ōzutsu Takeshi is a former sumo wrestler from Mie, Japan. Beginning his professional career in May 1971, he was ranked in the top makuuchi division continuously from March 1979 to January 1992, and his ... Wikipedia

Kotokaze Kōki.label: Kotokaze Kōki
Kotokaze Kōki.description: Kotokaze Kōki is a former sumo wrestler from Tsu, Mie, Japan. His highest rank was ōzeki. Wikipedia

Mienoumi Tsuyoshi.label: Mienoumi Tsuyoshi
Mienoumi Tsuyoshi.description: Mienoumi Tsuyoshi is a former champion sumo wrestler, the 57th yokozuna of the sport. He is the founder of Musashigawa stable and a former chairman of the Japan Sumo Association. He was born in Matsusaka, Mie, Japan. Wikipedia

Tamanoshima Arata.label: Tamanoshima Arata
Tamanoshima Arata.description: Tamanoshima Arata is a former sumo wrestler from Izumizaki, Fukushima, Japan. A former amateur champion, he made his professional debut in 1998, reaching the top makuuchi division at the end of 2000. Wikipedia

Onogawa Kisaburō.label: Onogawa Kisaburō
Onogawa Kisaburō.description: Onogawa Kisaburō was a sumo wrestler from Ōtsu, Shiga Prefecture, Japan. He was the sport's 5th Yokozuna. Wikipedia

Gōeidō Gōtarō.label: Gōeidō Gōtarō
Gōeidō Gōtarō.description: Gōeidō Gōtarō is a sumo wrestler from Osaka Prefecture, Japan. He made his professional debut in January 2005 and reached the top makuuchi division in September 2007. His highest rank to date has been sekiwake, which he achieved in May 2009. Wikipedia

Inazuma Raigorō.label: Inazuma Raigorō
Inazuma Raigorō.description: Inazuma Raigorō was a sumo wrestler from Inashiki, Ibaraki Prefecture, Japan. He was the sport's 7th Yokozuna. Inazuma means lightning in Japanese. Wikipedia

Kisenosato Yutaka.label: Kisenosato Yutaka
Kisenosato Yutaka.description: Kisenosato Yutaka is a sumo wrestler from Ibaraki, Japan. He made his professional debut in 2002, and reached the top makuuchi division in 2004 at the age of just 18. His highest rank to date is ōzeki, which he reached in January 2012. Wikipedia

Toyonishiki Kiichiro.label: Toyonishiki Kiichiro
Toyonishiki Kiichiro.description: Toyonishiki Kiichiro was a Japanese-American sumo wrestler who joined the sport shortly before World War II. He was one of the first foreign-born wrestlers to reach the top makuuchi division. Wikipedia

Wakanami Jun.label: Wakanami Jun
Wakanami Jun.description: Wakanami Jun was a sumo wrestler from Iwai, Ibaraki, Japan. His highest rank was komusubi. He won a top division tournament championship in March 1968. He was also a sumo coach. Wikipedia
Wakanami Jun.Born: March 1, 1941, Sashima District, Ibaraki, Ibaraki Prefecture, Japan

Baruto Kaito.label: Baruto Kaito
Baruto Kaito.description: Baruto Kaito is a former professional sumo wrestler from Estonia. Making his debut in May 2004, he was one of only two Estonians ever to join the sport in Japan, and the first to reach the top division, ... Wikipedia

Kakuryū Rikisaburō.label: Kakuryū Rikisaburō
Kakuryū Rikisaburō.description: Kakuryū Rikisaburō is a professional sumo wrestler from Sükhbaatar Province, Mongolia. He has been a member of the top makuuchi division since November 2006 and has earned nine special prizes, seven of those for technique. Wikipedia

Shōtenrō Taishi.label: Shōtenrō Taishi
Shōtenrō Taishi.description: Shōtenrō Taishi is a sumo wrestler from Khovd Province, Mongolia. He joined professional sumo in 2001 and was known as Musashiryū Taishi until 2007. Wikipedia

Tokitenkū Yoshiaki.label: Tokitenkū Yoshiaki
Tokitenkū Yoshiaki.description: Tokitenkū Yoshiaki is a sumo wrestler. He made his professional debut in 2002, reaching the top makuuchi division just two years later. The highest rank he has reached is komusubi, which he has held for three tournaments so far. Wikipedia

Kasugaō Katsumasa.label: Kasugaō Katsumasa
Kasugaō Katsumasa.description: Kasugaō Katsumasa 春日王 克昌 is a former Japanese sumo wrestler from Incheon, South Korea. He was the first sumo wrestler to reach the top makuuchi division officially representing South Korea. Wikipedia

Takanoyama Shuntaro.label: Takanoyama Shuntarō
Takanoyama Shuntaro.description: Takanoyama Shuntarō is a sumo wrestler from Prague, Czech Republic. He is the first man from the Czech Republic to join the professional sport in Japan. Wikipedia

Takamisugi Takakatsu.label: Takamisugi Takakatsu
Takamisugi Takakatsu.description: Takamisugi Takakatsu is a former sumo wrestler from Kawasaki, Kanagawa, Japan. His highest rank was komusubi. He is now a coach at Takanohana stable. Wikipedia

Hamanoshima Keishi.label: Hamanoshima Keishi
Hamanoshima Keishi.description: 'Hamanoshima Keishi is a former sumo wrestler from Uto, Kumamoto Prefecture, Japan. His highest rank was komusubi. A former amateur champion at Nihon University, he made his professional debut in January 1992, joining Mihogaseki stable. Wikipedia

Taihō Kōki.label: Taihō Kōki
Taihō Kōki.description: Taihō Kōki was the 48th Yokozuna in the Japanese sport of sumo wrestling. He is generally regarded as the greatest sumo wrestler of the post-war period. Wikipedia

Kōji Kitao.label: Kōji Kitao
Kōji Kitao.description: Kōji Kitao is a former sumo wrestler and professional wrestler, born in Mie, Japan. He was sumo's 60th Yokozuna, and the only yokozuna in sumo history not to win a top division tournament championship. Wikipedia
Movies: UFC Classics Ultimate Fighting Championship Vol. 9

Tochitsukasa Tetsuo.label: Tochitsukasa Tetsuo
Tochitsukasa Tetsuo.description: Tochitsukasa Tetsuo is a former sumo wrestler from Nakagawa, Nagoya, Aichi Prefecture, Japan. His highest rank was sekiwake. He is now the head coach of Irumagawa stable. Wikipedia

Tokusegawa Masanao.label: Tokusegawa Masanao
Tokusegawa Masanao.description: Tokusegawa Masano is a former sumo wrestler from Ulan Bator, Mongolia. Joining the professional sport in 2003, he entered the top division for the first time in March 2010, and rose to the middle maegashira ranks. Wikipedia

Daidō Kenji.label: Daidō Kenji
Daidō Kenji.description: Daidō Kenji is a professional sumo wrestler or rikishi. He made his debut in 2005, reaching the top division six years later, debuting in the July, 2011 tournament. His highest rank has been maegashira #9. Wikipedia

Sagatsukasa Hiroyuki.label: Sagatsukasa Hiroyuki
Sagatsukasa Hiroyuki.description: Sagatsukasa Hiroyuki is a sumo wrestler from Mishima, Shizuoka Prefecture, Japan. His highest rank has been maegashira 9. Wikipedia

Haguroyama Sojō.label: Haguroyama Sojō
Haguroyama Sojō.description: Haguroyama Sojō is a former sumo wrestler from Hokkaidō, Japan. Wikipedia

Hayateumi Hidehito.label: Hayateumi Hidehito
Hayateumi Hidehito.description: Hayateumi Hidehito is a former sumo wrestler from Aomori, Japan. His highest rank was sekiwake. Wikipedia

Kongō Masahiro.label: Kongō Masahiro
Kongō Masahiro.description: Kongō Masahiro is a former sumo wrestler from Hokkaidō, Japan. His highest rank was sekiwake and he won a top division tournament championship in 1975. He was a sumo coach and head of the Nishonoseki stable from 1976 until 2013. Wikipedia

Kotoshōgiku Kazuhiro.label: Kotoshōgiku Kazuhiro
Kotoshōgiku Kazuhiro.description: Kotoshōgiku Kazuhiro, is a sumo wrestler. He made his professional debut in 2002, reaching the top division in 2005. He has earned seven special prizes in his career and been runner-up in two tournaments. He wrestles for Sadogatake stable. Wikipedia

Wakanohana Kanji I.label: Wakanohana Kanji I
Wakanohana Kanji I.description:
Wakanohana Kanji I was a sumo wrestler, the sport's 45th Yokozuna.
Wakanohana's younger brother was the late former ōzeki Takanohana Kenshi and he was the uncle of Takanohana Kōji and Wakanohana Masaru. Wikipedia

Aoiyama Kōsuke.label: Aoiyama Kōsuke
Aoiyama Kōsuke.description: Aoiyama Kōsuke is a professional sumo wrestler or rikishi. He made his debut in 2009, reaching the top division two years later, debuting in the November 2011 tournament where he won the Fighting Spirit award along with Wakakōyū. Wikipedia

Fujiazuma Kazuyoshi.label: Fujiazuma Kazuyoshi
Fujiazuma Kazuyoshi.description: Fujiazuma Kazuyoshi is a professional sumo wrestler from Tokyo, Japan. His highest rank to date has been maegashira 4. Wikipedia

Sadanofuji Akihiro.label: Sadanofuji Akihiro
Sadanofuji Akihiro.description: Sadanofuji Akihiro is a sumo wrestler from Kazusa, Nagasaki, Japan. The highest rank he has reached is maegashira 10. Wikipedia

Takarafuji Daisuke.label: Takarafuji Daisuke
Takarafuji Daisuke.description: Takarafuji Daisuke is a sumo wrestler from Nakadomari, Aomori, Japan. The highest rank he has reached is maegashira 3. Wikipedia
Takarafuji Daisuke.Born: February 18, 1987 (age 27), Nakadomari, Aomori, Aomori Prefecture, Japan

Kōryū Tadaharu.label: Kōryū Tadaharu
Kōryū Tadaharu.description: Kōryū Tadaharu is a Mongolian former sumo wrestler from Ulan Bator. His highest rank was maegashira 11. He was forced to retire from sumo in 2011 after being found guilty of match-fixing. Wikipedia

Tosayutaka Yūya.label: Tosayutaka Yūya
Tosayutaka Yūya.description: Tosayutaka Yūya is a sumo wrestler from Tosa City, Kōchi Prefecture, Japan. He made his professional debut in March 2007, reaching the top makuuchi division in July 2009. His highest rank has been maegashira 1. Wikipedia

Higonoumi Naoya.label: Higonoumi Naoya
Higonoumi Naoya.description: Higonoumi Naoya is a former sumo wrestler from Kumamoto, Japan. After his retirement he opened up Kise stable. Wikipedia

Asanowaka Takehiko.label: Asanowaka Takehiko
Asanowaka Takehiko.description: Asanowaka Takehiko is a former sumo wrestler from Ichinomiya, Aichi Prefecture, Japan. His highest rank was maegashira 1. He is now a sumo coach. Wikipedia

Onigatani Saiji.label: Onigatani Saiji
Onigatani Saiji.description: Onigatani Saiji was a Japanese sumo wrestler who is known for being active in the top makuuchi division at the age of 51, which is a record after the beginning of the Meiji era. Wikipedia

Takayasu Akira.label: Takayasu Akira
Takayasu Akira.description: Takayasu Akira is a Japanese sumo wrestler. He made his professional debut in 2005, and reached the top makuuchi division in 2011, the first wrestler born in the Heisei era to do so. His highest rank has been komusubi. Wikipedia

Aminishiki Ryūji.label: Aminishiki Ryūji
Aminishiki Ryūji.description: Aminishiki Ryūji is a Japanese sumo wrestler. He made his professional debut in 1997 and has been ranked in the top division since 2000. Wikipedia

Kirishima Kazuhiro.label: Kirishima Kazuhiro
Kirishima Kazuhiro.description: Kirishima Kazuhiro is a former sumo wrestler from Makizono, Kagoshima, Japan, who held the second highest rank of ōzeki from 1990 to 1992 and won one top division tournament championship. Wikipedia

Masuiyama Daishirō II.label: Masuiyama Daishirō II
Masuiyama Daishirō II.description: Masuiyama Daishirō is a former sumo wrestler from Hyōgo, Japan. In 1980 he became the oldest man to be promoted to the rank of ōzeki in the modern era. He is now a sumo coach and an elder of the Japan Sumo Association under the name Mihogaseki. Wikipedia

Teila Tuli.label: Teila Tuli
Teila Tuli.description: Teila Tuli, also known as Taylor Wily is an actor and a former sumo wrestler and mixed martial artist. He is from Honolulu, Hawaii and is of Samoan descent. He is commonly known for his recurring role as Kamekona on Hawaii Five-0. Wikipedia

Asashio Tarō IV.label: Asashio Tarō IV
Asashio Tarō IV.description: Asashio Tarō IV is a former sumo wrestler from Muroto, Kochi, Japan. His highest rank was ōzeki. He is currently the head coach of Takasago stable. Wikipedia
Asashio Tarō IV.Born: December 9, 1955 (age 58), Aki District, Kōchi, Kōchi Prefecture, Japan

Dejima Takeharu.label: Dejima Takeharu
Dejima Takeharu.description: Dejima Takeharu is a former sumo wrestler from Kanazawa, Ishikawa, Japan. A former amateur champion, he made his professional debut in 1996, reaching the top makuuchi division the following year. Wikipedia

Haguroyama Masaji.label: Haguroyama Masaji
Haguroyama Masaji.description: Haguroyama Masaji was a sumo wrestler from Nakanokuchi, Niigata, Japan. He was the sport's 36th yokozuna. Wikipedia

Iwakiyama Ryūta.label: Iwakiyama Ryūta
Iwakiyama Ryūta.description: Iwakiyama Ryūta, is a former sumo wrestler. A former amateur sumo champion, he turned professional in 2000 and reached the top division at the end of 2002. The highest rank he reached was komusubi. Wikipedia

Kasuganishiki Takahiro.label: Kasuganishiki Takahiro
Kasuganishiki Takahiro.description: Kasuganishiki Takahiro is a former sumo wrestler from Misaki, Isumi District, Chiba Prefecture, Japan. He made his debut in 1991, reaching the top makuuchi division in 2002 His highest rank was maegashira 5. Wikipedia

Kotonowaka Terumasa.label: Kotonowaka Terumasa
Kotonowaka Terumasa.description: Kotonowaka Terumasa is a former sumo wrestler from Obanazawa, Yamagata prefecture, Japan. He made his professional debut in 1984 and after reaching the top makuuchi division in 1990 he remained there for 15 years until his retirement in 2005. Wikipedia

Miyagino Nishikinosuke.label: Miyagino Nishikinosuke
Miyagino Nishikinosuke.description: Miyagino Nishikinosuke was a Japanese sumo wrestler. His highest rank was sekiwake. He was an active top makuuchi division wrestler at the age of 52, which is the all-time recognized record. Wikipedia

Tamanoumi Masahiro.label: Tamanoumi Masahiro
Tamanoumi Masahiro.description: Tamanoumi Masahiro, was a sumo wrestler, born in Aichi, Japan. He was the sport's 51st yokozuna. Wikipedia
Tamanoumi Masahiro.Died: October 11, 1971, Toranomon, Minato, Tokyo, Tokyo, Japan

Tochinoshin Tsuyoshi.label: Tochinoshin Tsuyoshi
Tochinoshin Tsuyoshi.description: Tochinoshin Tsuyoshi is a professional sumo wrestler from Mtskheta, Georgia. He is a member of the Kasugano stable and made his debut in March 2006. He reached the top makuuchi division just two years later in May 2008. Wikipedia
